  "Both connect derivatives and differences; the FTC connects derivatives and integrals, which the MVT motivates": "",
  "The MVT states f(b)-f(a) = f'(c)(b-a), relating the global change to a local derivative. The FTC extends this: f(b)-f(a) = integral of f'. Both connect local (derivative) and global (change) behavior.": "",
  "What does it mean to say two functions 'differ by a constant'?": "",
  "f(x) and g(x) have the same domain": "",
  "f(x) - g(x) = C for some fixed constant C, for all x in the domain": "",
  "f'(x) = g'(x) + C": "",
  "f(x) = g(x) at some point": "",
  "Differing by a constant means the gap between f and g is the same everywhere: f(x) = g(x) + C. This is the MVT corollary when f' = g'.": "",
  "What is the 'racetrack principle'?": "",
  "A theorem about circular motion": "",
  "If f > g at one point, then f > g everywhere": "",
  "If f'(x) >= g'(x) on [a,b] and f(a) = g(a), then f(x) >= g(x) on [a,b]": "",
  "The fastest car always wins the race": "",
  "The racetrack principle (a consequence of the MVT): if two runners start together and one is always at least as fast, that runner stays ahead.": "",
